Part 4: Using Garmin Vivoactive 5 with Your Training Plan

Initial Setup (December 2025)

Step 1: Establish Heart Rate Zones

  1. Go to Garmin Connect app (web or mobile)

  2. Click "Settings" "User Settings" "Heart Rate and Power Zones"

  3. Select "Heart Rate Zones" tab

  4. Choose zone calculation method: "% of Max Heart Rate" (easiest if you don't have FTP)

  5. Enter your max heart rate:

    • Estimate: 220 age = 220 48 = 172 bpm

    • Or perform a test: 3-minute all-out effort, followed by 3-minute easy, then another 3-minute all-out; take peak HR from second effort

    • For this plan, use 172 bpm

  6. Auto-populate zones or manually enter:

    • Zone 1 (Z1): 5060% = 86103 bpm (recovery, very easy)

    • Zone 2 (Z2): 6075% = 103129 bpm (endurance, easy)

    • Zone 3 (Z3): 7585% = 129146 bpm (tempo, moderate-hard)

    • Zone 4 (Z4): 8594% = 146162 bpm (threshold, hard)

    • Zone 5 (Z5): 94100% = 162172 bpm (VO2/anaerobic, maximum effort)

  7. Save and sync to your Garmin Vivoactive 5

Step 2: Enable HR Alerts on Your Watch

  1. On your Garmin watch, go to "Settings" "Activities & Apps" "Cycling" (or custom cycling profile)

  2. Select "Alerts" "Add New Alert"

  3. Create two alerts:

    • Lower HR alert: Set to 105 bpm (enforces easy effort on Z1 rides; warns if you're slipping into Z2 when you intend Z1)

    • Upper HR alert: Set to 150 bpm (prevents going too hard on recovery days; useful after hard weeks)

  4. Set alerts to "Vibration + Tone" so you feel and hear when outside zone

  5. Repeat for each main profile (Cycling, Virtual Cycling, etc.)

Step 3: Enable RHR and HRV Monitoring

  1. In Garmin Connect app, go to "Health" or "Pulse Ox & Hydration" section

  2. Enable "Resting Heart Rate (RHR)" tracking (automatic; measures upon wake)

  3. Enable "Heart Rate Variability (HRV)" if available on Vivoactive 5 (check manual; some Garmin watches have limited HRV)

  4. Set "Daily Snapshot" to display HR summary each morning

  5. Monitor trend: Take note of your baseline RHR (should be ~5565 bpm at rest). If RHR rises >5 bpm for 3+ consecutive days, consider extra rest

Step 4: Create Custom Data Screens

  1. On your Vivoactive 5, go to "Settings" "Data Screens" (or "Cycling" profile "Data Screens")

  2. Add a screen showing:

    • Heart Rate Zone indicator (shows which zone you're in)

    • Current HR and % of max HR

    • Average HR for this ride

    • Time in Zone (if available)

  3. Example data screen during a ride:

    • Current HR: 125 bpm

    • Zone: Z2 (61% HR max)

    • Avg HR this ride: 118 bpm

    • Time in Z2 this ride: 32:45

Weekly Workflow with Garmin

Every morning (upon waking):

  1. Sync your Vivoactive 5 to Garmin Connect via Bluetooth

  2. Check Daily Snapshot: review yesterday's HR data, sleep, steps

  3. Note your RHR this morning (Garmin reports in Health section). Compare to your weekly average baseline:

    • If RHR is >5 bpm above baseline AND you have a hard session planned, consider swapping today's session with tomorrow's rest day

    • If RHR is elevated but you're feeling okay, proceed as planned; just monitor during warm-up

During each ride:

  1. Start your activity: "Cycling" Begin

  2. Watch stays in your custom data screen showing HR and zone

  3. HR alerts will vibrate if you go outside your target zone

  4. Goal for each session type:

    • Z1 ride: Keep HR alert set to 105 bpm; if you hear vibration, ease off (chat, smile test)

    • Z2 ride: Aim for average HR 110125 bpm

    • Z3 ride: Aim for average HR 135145 bpm (on climbs)

    • Z4 ride: Aim for average HR 145155 bpm (intervals)

    • Z5 intervals: Max HR 160172 bpm (very brief, during hard efforts only)

  5. Post-ride: Stop activity, watch automatically logs session

After each ride (sync within 1 hour):

  1. Connect to phone, Garmin Connect app auto-syncs

  2. Review ride summary in Garmin Connect:

    • Duration, distance, elevation gain, average HR, max HR, calories burned

    • Compare average HR to target zone (example: if Z1 ride, was avg HR 105115?)

  3. Record perceived exertion (110 RPE) in ride notes (tap ride "Edit" add note like "RPE 3, felt easy, good recovery")

Weekly review (Sunday evening):

  1. Open Garmin Connect, view "Week" summary

  2. Check:

    • Total training hours (should match plan: 67 in Dec, ramping to 10 by May)

    • HR trend: Is average HR on easy rides stable? Rising avg on same route = fatigue

    • RHR trend: Should be flat or slightly declining over weeks as fitness improves

  3. Export or screenshot for your records if using a spreadsheet to track weight/training balance

Part 5: Using Strava Premium with Your Training Plan

Initial Setup and Integration

Connect Garmin to Strava:

  1. Open Strava app (web or mobile)

  2. Go to "Settings" "Connected Apps" "Garmin Connect"

  3. Authorize sync (one-time; thereafter rides auto-upload within 12 hours)

  4. Select "Fitness & Freshness" to enable the Fitness/Fatigue/Form chart

Understanding Fitness, Fatigue, and Form

Fitness (chronic training load):

  • Represents cumulative training effect over ~4 weeks

  • Calculated from each ride's Training Load (intensity duration)

  • Trends upward with consistent training; declines ~2.5% per day if no training

  • Goal: Steady increase from ~30 (baseline in Dec) to ~5565 (peak by June 20)

Fatigue (acute training load):

  • Represents accumulated fatigue from recent hard efforts (~12 weeks)

  • Spikes up when you do intense sessions; decays quickly on easy/rest days

  • Goal: Keep elevated during hard weeks (4060), drop during taper (<30)

Form (Training Stress Balance):

  • Form = Fitness Fatigue

  • Positive Form (e.g., +20): You are fresh relative to fitness; good day to race or test yourself

  • Negative Form (e.g., 20): You are fatigued; good day for recovery or easy ride

  • Ideal range for long event prep: 10 to +10 (balanced; not overly fatigued, not overly fresh)

  • Race day ideal: +5 to +15 (fresh with good fitness)

Example tracking (hypothetical):

  • Early December: Fitness 25, Fatigue 20, Form +5 (baseline, good starting point)

  • Late December (after 2 weeks consistency): Fitness 32, Fatigue 28, Form +4 (fitness building, fatigue managed)

  • End of February (base phase peak): Fitness 50, Fatigue 35, Form +15 (good fitness, relatively fresh)

  • Mid-April (build phase): Fitness 58, Fatigue 45, Form +13 (fitness peaking, some fatigue accumulating)

  • Mid-May (build phase peak): Fitness 68, Fatigue 55, Form +13 (peak fitness, moderate fatigue)

  • June 20 (before taper): Fitness 72, Fatigue 48, Form +24 (peak fitness, beginning to recover)

  • June 27 (race day): Fitness 70, Fatigue 25, Form +45 (very fresh with maintained fitnessready to race)

Weekly Strava Workflow

After each ride syncs (usually 12 hours):

  1. Open Strava app/web

  2. Review your Fitness & Freshness chart (line graph at top of dashboard)

  3. Check if Fitness is trending upward as expected (should ramp ~25 points per week during base/build, flatten during taper)

  4. If Fitness is flat or declining unexpectedly: You may not be hitting volume targets; add an easy ride or extend a long ride

  5. If Fatigue is much higher than expected: You may have done too many hard sessions; scale back next week's intensity

Weekly summary (Sunday evening):

  1. View "Weekly Stats" in Strava

  2. Record:

    • Total hours/distance/elevation

    • Average HR on easy rides (should stay consistent, e.g., 110120 bpm)

    • Max HR achieved (highest during hard efforts)

    • Fitness score (note in spreadsheet)

  3. Check "Segments" for notable climbs ridden this week; compare average pace to previous weeks (should be stable on easy rides; faster on threshold rides)

  4. Compare to target weekly structure in your plan:

    • Base phase: 67 hours (mostly Z1Z2), 1 hard session

    • Build phase: 810 hours (70% easy, 20% tempo, 10% hard), 2 threshold/tempo + 1 long

    • Taper: 56 hours (minimal intensity)

Using Strava Segment Data to Validate Training

Segments as training gauge:

  • Easy ride pace: On a familiar climb you've ridden many times, your segment time should be ~1020% slower than current peak pace (good sign you're not going too hard)

  • Threshold ride pace: On same climb, ridden at Z34, you should be within 510% of your personal best time

  • Example: Your Alpe d'Huez segment best time is 50 min. In base phase, easy rides should take 6065 min (90100 RPM, controlled effort). In build phase threshold rides should take 5255 min (9095 RPM, sustained effort).

Avoid segment hunting:

  • Don't obsess over segment times during base phase (they will be slow by design)

  • Use segments as data points, not motivation; your plan is the target, not Strava leaderboards

Part 6: Strength & Mobility Training (23 sessions per week, 2530 min each)

Why Strength Matters for La Marmotte

Cycling alone builds leg strength but leaves core, glute stability, and postural strength underdeveloped. This increases injury risk and limits your ability to generate power on climbs. A simple bodyweight routine 23x/week (2530 min) will:

  • Stabilize your core for sustained climbing efforts

  • Strengthen glutes (primary climbing muscles)

  • Improve hip mobility and lower-back resilience

  • Reduce fatigue on long rides

Session Template A: Core & Glute Emphasis (25 min, all bodyweight)

Warm-up (3 min):

  • 20 arm circles

  • 10 bodyweight squats (slow, full range)

  • 5 cat-cow stretches

Main Circuit (20 min: 3 rounds, ~6 min per round):

  1. Glute Bridges (315 reps): Lie on back, knees bent 90, push hips high, squeeze glutes at top; hold 1 sec. Rest 30 sec.

  2. Single-Leg Glute Bridge (38 per leg): Same as above, lift one leg off ground; hold top for 2 sec. Rest 30 sec.

  3. Plank Hold (33045 sec): Forearms on ground, body in straight line, engage core. Rest 30 sec.

  4. Side Plank (32030 sec per side): Lie on one side, forearm on ground, lift hips; hold. Rest 30 sec.

  5. Bodyweight Squat (312 reps): Slow descent, controlled ascent; keep chest up. Rest 30 sec.

  6. Walking Lunge (310 per leg): Step forward, lower back knee toward ground, drive back up. Rest 30 sec.

Cool-down / Stretching (2 min):

  • 30 sec: Child's pose

  • 30 sec: Pigeon pose (each side) or quad stretch

  • 30 sec: Forward fold

Session Template B: Climbing-Specific Strength (25 min, minimal equipment)

Warm-up (3 min):

  • 20 arm circles

  • 10 bodyweight squats

  • 5 bird dogs (opposite arm + leg reach)

Main Circuit (20 min: 3 rounds, ~6 min per round):

  1. Step-Ups (312 per leg): Use a step, bench, or sturdy chair; step up, drive knee up, step down. Rest 30 sec.

  2. Bulgarian Split Squats (310 per leg): Rear foot on low step/bench, front leg lunges deep; rear leg does light work. Rest 30 sec.

  3. Dead Bug (310 per side): Lie on back, lift opposite arm + leg, lower controlled; alternate. Rest 30 sec.

  4. Glute Bridge Hold + Pulse (315 pulses): Hold glute bridge top position, pulse hips up/down 15 quickly. Rest 30 sec.

  5. Reverse Lunges (310 per leg): Step back, lunge deep, drive forward. Rest 30 sec.

  6. Wall Sit (33045 sec): Back to wall, knees 90, hold. Rest 30 sec.

Cool-down / Stretching (2 min):

  • 1 min: Cat-cow stretches

  • 1 min: Hip opener (figure-4 or pigeon)

Session Template C: Yoga / Mobility Flow (25 min)

Focus on hip, lower-back, and shoulder mobility. Cycle through at comfortable pace (no rushing):

  • Sun Salutation (3): 3 full rounds (walk feet back to plank, push-up or knees-down, upward dog, downward dog, walk feet forward, forward fold, rise to standing)

  • Warrior I (Hold 30 sec each side): Build heat, open hips

  • Warrior II (Hold 30 sec each side): Strengthen legs, open hips further

  • Triangle Pose (Hold 2030 sec each side): Hamstring and side-body stretch

  • Child's Pose (12 min): Deep relaxation, lower-back release

  • Pigeon Pose (12 min each side): Deep hip opener (key for cyclists)

  • Happy Baby (12 min): Hip and lower-back release

  • Supine Twist (30 sec each side): Spine and IT band

  • Final Savasana (23 min): Lie flat, relax

Integration into Your Weekly Plan

DecemberMay:

  • Option 1 (Busy weeks): 2 sessions, 25 min each Tuesday (Template A) + Friday (Template B or C)

  • Option 2 (Normal weeks): 3 sessions Tuesday (Template A) + Thursday (Template B) + Saturday morning (Template C)

June (Taper & Race Prep):

  • Scale back to 12 light sessions per week (mostly Template C mobility, 20 min)

  • Avoid heavy leg strength in final 2 weeks; mobility and core maintenance only

Part 7: Recovery, Overtraining Prevention, and Sleep

Signs of Overtraining

Monitor for these red flags:

  1. Elevated resting heart rate (+510 bpm above baseline for 3+ consecutive days)

  2. Poor or restless sleep (taking >30 min to fall asleep, waking multiple times, <6 h total)

  3. Motivation drops: Dread upcoming rides, low mental energy during training

  4. Performance decline: Can't hit target HR zones, legs feel heavy, unable to sustain efforts

  5. Persistent muscle soreness: Legs sore >3 days after hard sessions (normal is 12 days)

  6. Elevated resting heart rate + low HRV: Parasympathetic nervous system stressed (sign of inadequate recovery)

  7. Illness: Frequent colds, sore throats, lingering infections (immune suppression from overtraining)

  8. Mood changes: Irritability, anxiety, difficulty concentrating (CNS fatigue)

Prevention Strategy

Golden Rules:

  1. Include at least 12 complete rest days per week (no training, minimal activity)

  2. Include 1 recovery week every 34 weeks: Reduce volume 4050%, keep intensity low (all Z1Z2)

  3. Sleep target: 79 hours per night (non-negotiable; recovery happens in sleep)

  4. Nutrition adequate to training load (don't create excessive calorie deficit when training hard)

  5. Listen to your body: If RHR elevated or motivation low, take an extra rest day or reduce intensity

Sleep Optimization

Sleep is when your body adapts and gets stronger. Poor sleep will undo good training:

  • Consistent sleep schedule: Bed at 10:30 pm, wake 6:30 am (7 h minimum)

  • Sleep hygiene:

    • No screens (phone, TV) after 9:30 pm

    • Bedroom cool (6568F / 1820C), dark, quiet

    • Avoid caffeine after 2 pm

    • No heavy meals within 3 hours of bed

  • Wind-down routine (30 min before bed):

    • Read or listen to calm podcast

    • Light stretching or yoga

    • Breathwork (4 sec inhale, 6 sec exhale, 3 min total)

  • Track sleep in Garmin: Vivoactive 5 tracks sleep automatically; monitor weekly average (should be 6.58 h). If <6 h multiple nights, priority: extend sleep before adding training

Recovery Days / Weeks

Easy recovery day (12 per week):

  • Short easy spin 4560 min, Z1Z2 only (HR <120 bpm)

  • Purpose: Maintain aerobic system, promote blood flow, mental break

  • NOT a training session: Feel fresh and easy; chat, smile easily

Complete rest day (12 per week, especially week 1 of each month):

  • No structured training; minimal activity (walk 30 min, stretching, gardening)

  • Purpose: Allow complete nervous system recovery

  • Mental benefit: Builds motivation for next training block

Recovery week (every 34 weeks, e.g., last week of Jan, last week of Feb, early April, mid-May):

  • Reduce volume 4050% vs. peak week (example: if peak is 8 hours, recovery week is 4.5 hours)

  • All intensity at Z1Z2 (no threshold, no high-intensity intervals)

  • Add extra easy spinning or walking

  • Purpose: Allows body to adapt to accumulated training, prevents accumulated fatigue

  • Common result: You feel stronger in week 1 after recovery week (supercompensation)

Part 8: Event-Specific Strategy and Preparation

La Marmotte Profile & Key Demands

The Race:

  • Distance: 177 km

  • Total climbing: 5,030 m over 4 major cols

  • Climbing breakdown:

    1. Col du Glandon: 22 km, 1,024 m (4.6% avg gradient, ~2 h 15 min)

    2. Col du Tlgraphe: 12 km, 1,120 m (9.3% avg, ~1 h 30 min)

    3. Col du Galibier: 23 km, 1,642 m (7.1% avg, ~3 h; includes highest point at 2,642 m elevation)

    4. Alpe d'Huez: 13.8 km, 1,860 m (8.6% avg, ~1 h 45 min2 h 30 min depending on pace; most psychological challenge)

  • Descents: ~1,700 m total; opportunity to recover and refuel

  • Finisher time range: 6 h 30 min (elite) to 14 hours (cut-off)

  • Weather wild card: Can vary from 0C at Galibier to 25C in Bourg d'Oisans; thunderstorms common

  • Mental challenge: Final 60 km (Galibier + Alpe d'Huez) on tired legs after 6+ hours of riding

Your Target Strategy: Safe, Comfortable Finish

Your approach: Not racing the clock, but executing a pacing strategy that gets you to the finish strong and satisfied.

Key target metrics (based on 9482 kg; improving power-to-weight):

  • FTP estimate (if you haven't tested): ~280300 W (assuming recreational cyclist)

  • Power-to-weight start (94 kg): ~3.03.2 W/kg

  • Power-to-weight race day (82 kg, same FTP): ~3.43.7 W/kg (improvement via weight loss)

  • Target climbing intensity: 7580% FTP (~210240 W), which is Zone 34 (sustainable for 23 hour climbs)

  • Target finishing HR: 130145 bpm average on climbs (conversational effort on easy sections)

  • Target finishing time: 911 hours (safe, not rushed)

Pacing Strategy by Climb

Pre-Race (Bourg d'Oisans to Glandon base, ~30 km, 1 h 30 min):

  • Effort: Very easy (Z1Z2), ~100 bpm average HR

  • Goal: Settle in, warm legs, find group, practice bunch riding

  • Fueling: Water + electrolytes, 1 gel at 1 h mark if needed

  • Mindset: "It's only the start; conserve energy"

Col du Glandon (22 km, ~2 h 15 min):

  • Pacing: Steady (Z3, ~75% FTP), 140150 bpm

  • Strategy: Climb at conversational pace (you should be able to speak short sentences but not sing). Don't chase other riders; let them go.

  • Cadence: 8595 rpm (smooth pedaling, avoid grinding low cadence)

  • Fueling: 1 gel at 45 min mark (take with water), sip electrolyte bottle every 1015 min

  • Mental: "Steady, smooth, many more hours to go"

  • Exit: Soft descent, recover breathing, reset for next climb

Col du Tlgraphe (12 km, ~1 h 30 min):

  • Pacing: Moderate (Z3Z4, 7580% FTP), 145155 bpm

  • Strategy: Slightly harder than Glandon (legs are fresher). Push a bit on easier sections (56% gradient), ease on steeper sections (>10%).

  • Fueling: Eat energy bar now (if you've eaten gels twice already) or 1 gel; sip electrolytes

  • Mental: "Two down, two to go"

  • Exit: Prepare for long Galibier climb ahead

Col du Galibier (23 km, ~3 h climbing):

  • Pacing: Conservative (Z3, 7075% FTP, 135145 bpm) for first 15 km; increase to Z34 (150155 bpm) for final 8 km

  • Strategy: "Slow up, strong home" approach. First 15 km should feel VERY easy (you're getting tired now, 5+ hours in). Save energy for final push.

    • Km 07 (Chalets section, ~8% gradient): Steady, conversational, 70% FTP

    • Km 715 (Mid-Galibier, mixed 79%): Maintain steady effort, eat more fuel

    • Km 1523 (Final push to Col, steeper, 911%): Pick up effort slightly (7580% FTP), power through mentally

  • Elevation note: You'll pass 2,000 m elevation around km 1214. Breathing harder is normal (altitude effect minimal at 2,642 m, but still noticeable).

  • Fueling: Start with 1 gel at km 5, another at km 12. Sip electrolytes constantly (aim for ~600 ml per hour). Consider energy bar if stomach feels okay.

  • Mental: This is the hardest climbpain is expected. Mantra: "I am strong, I am prepared, I will finish"

  • Exit: Long technical descent (be careful, wet roads possible in storms); recover, reset mind for final climb

Alpe d'Huez (13.8 km, ~2 h climbing; the final boss):

  • Pacing: Three-part strategy:

    1. La Garde section (Km 03, 10.4% gradient, steepest part): Climb "as slowly as possible" (Z2Z3, 130140 bpm). Don't attack; settle in. This is where many riders blow up.

    2. Mid-section (Km 310, 8.4% gradient, easiest part): "Stamp on it" (Z3Z4, 145155 bpm). Take advantage of easier gradient; make up time here.

    3. Final push (Km 1013.8, mixed 710%, final hairpins to finish): "Go as fast as you can" (Z4, 150160 bpm). Mentally race the last 4 km; visualization helps; think "I'm almost there."

  • Fueling: Final gel at km 2 (easy section), one more gel at km 8 if stomach allows. Electrolytes to the end. You may not want food at this point; focus on fluids.

  • Mental: You've been riding 89 hours. Alpe d'Huez is the finish line; the climb will end. Every turn of pedals gets you closer.

  • Exit: The final turn at the top leads to the finish line (~1 km finish run). Celebrate!

Part 9: How to Modify Weeks When Work or Coaching Gets Busy

Busy Week Strategy (e.g., work conference or heavy football schedule)

If a week has unexpected high work stress or extra football sessions (pushing you above normal 810 hour work + coaching load):

Priority Hierarchy (what to skip first):

  1. First to skip: High-intensity session (threshold, VO2, intervals)

    • Replace with easy 1-hour spin or skip entirely

    • Reason: Intensity requires full recovery; without it, you risk overtraining during high-stress week

  2. Second to skip: One long ride (but keep the other, scaled down 2030%)

    • Replace Sunday 4-hour climb with 2.5-hour easy ride

    • Reason: Maintenance of base aerobic fitness more important than peak long-ride volume this week

  3. Third to skip: One strength session (but keep the other if possible)

    • Replace with 10-minute core routine (planks, glute bridges, dead bugs)

    • Reason: Some stimulus better than none; prioritize full recovery otherwise

  4. Never skip: 12 complete rest days

    • Non-negotiable; rest is when adaptation happens

Very Busy Week (6hour work + 10 hours coaching per week = massive stress)

If life stress is extreme (e.g., work deadline + end-of-season football tournament):

  • Option 1: Take a spontaneous recovery week early (all Z1Z2, 34 hours, lots of rest days)

  • Option 2: Replace all structured training with 34 easy 4560 min spins + 1 long easy (23 hours); skip intensity entirely

  • Result: You'll bounce back stronger the following week after life stress normalizes

Sick or Injured During Plan

Missed 23 days:

  • Resume plan as if no break (body bounces back quickly)

  • Skip next hard session; replace with easy week

Missed 1 week:

  • Return with reduced volume (50% of plan that week)

  • Skip intensity; all Z1Z2

  • Expect slight fatigue loss (~23% in Strava Fitness); you'll regain it quickly

Missed 2+ weeks:

  • Revert to Base Phase structure (all Z1Z2, no intensity)

  • Take 23 weeks to rebuild

  • Postpone race if within 3 weeks (injury/illness recovery not worth risk at Marmotte)
